Summary report 2015

UKMON

27 Nov 2016

## [1] "Dataset: ALL period 2015-01-02 to 2015-12-31"

Summary of activity

In 2015 a total of 23 cameras cntributed data to the UKMON repository. Together, these cameras recorded 29534 individual meteor observations. The number of recorded observations by station is as follows:

After applying quality criteria`we found that 5057 meteors were observed by more than one camera (Unified observations). The following shows a count of the number of meters observed by two, three, etc. cameras.

The number of unified observations as a percentage of individual observations is 17.1%. A breakdown of unified observation counts by stream (top ten) is as follows:

Fireball activity

A total of 12 fireballs were observed in the reporting period (r SelectYr`). Here we define a fireball as a meteor event with a magnitude of -4 or less. A breakdown by month and by shower is shown below.

The brightest (top 10) fireballs observed during 2015 were:

Magnitudes

The following graphs show the distribution of magnitudes:

The following plots shows the altitude of the atart and end of ablation for each individual meteor. The plot is in order of decreasing start height and gives a good visualisation of the depth of the ablation zone. Where in the atmosphere ablation occurs will depend on factors such as meteor velocity and composition.

The maximum observed altitude was 151.0 km and the minimum observed altitude was 16.2 km. The distribution of distances travelled through the ablation zone was as follows:
